{"text": "= = = = = = [40.3] Perturbation theory - motivation\n\nLet us consider a particle in a two dimensional box. On the left a rectangular box, and on the right a chaotic box.\n\nFor a regular box (with straight walls) we found: Enx;ny/(nx=Lx)2+ (ny=Ly)2, so if we change Lxwe get the energy\n\nlevel scheme which is drawn in the left panel of the following\n\ngure. But if we consider a chaotic box, we shall get\n\nenergy level scheme as on the right panel.\n\nLEn\n\nLEn\n\nThe spectrum is a function of a control parameter, which in the example above is the position of a wall. For generality\n\nlet us call this parameter X. The Hamiltonian is H(^Q;^P;X). Let us assume that we have calculated the levels either\n\nanalytically or numerically for X=X0. Next we change the control parameter to the value X=X0+\u000eX, and use\n\nthe notation \u000eX=\u0015for the small parameter. Possibly, if \u0015is small enough, we can linearize the Hamiltonian as\n\nfollows:\n\nH=H(Q;P;X0) +\u0015V(Q;P) =H0+\u0015V (40.10)\n\nWith or without this approximation we can try to calculate the new energy levels. But if we do not want or cannot\n\ndiagonalizeHfor the new value of Xwe can try to use a perturbation theory scheme. Obviously this scheme will\n\nwork only for small enough \u0015that do not \"mix\" the levels too much. There is some \"radius of convergence\" (in \u0015)\n\nbeyond which perturbation theory fails completely. In many practical cases X=X0is taken as the value for which\n\nthe Hamiltonian is simple and can be handled analytically. In atomic physics the control parameter Xis usually\n\neither the prefactor of the spin-orbit term, or an electric\n\neld or a magnetic\n\neld which are turned on.\n\nThere is another context in which perturbation theory is very useful. Given (say) a chaotic system, we would like to\n\npredict its response to a small change in one of its parameters. For example we may ask what is the response of the\n\nsystem to an external driving by either an electric or a magnetic\n\neld.", "embedding": [-0.0017666837, -0.017631138, 0.06354041, -0.0291587, -0.028838769, -0.019990431, -0.041543584, 0.0015335497, -0.07329642, 0.067890994, 0.025089467, 0.0080140615, -0.0055714245, -0.032746553, -0.023500055, 0.015033129, -0.023233376, -0.007915993, -0.054535195, 0.055824548, 0.054428604, 0.011073277, -0.08902055, -0.014254562, -0.031567547, 0.0018545116, 0.0105678225, 0.014789582, 0.0412152, 0.07562322, 0.019340629, -0.034571163, -0.015236937, -0.012507107, -0.0029478313, 0.03442506, -0.020600677, -0.028501233, 0.038195174, -0.035655938, 0.05522277, -0.017408561, -0.0018051125, -0.02046598, -0.049746417, 0.004157231, -0.02691666, 0.013098937, -0.018733224, -0.07464529, 0.003201095, -0.02310853, 0.035165098, -0.0207357, -0.0053715697, -0.000912449, 0.00819552, 0.030239021, -0.0043185703, 0.013328566, 0.021354299, -0.003595866, 0.0013579149, 0.0014775217, 0.0280358, 0.077454396, -0.043144666, 0.0107113, -0.0073113353, -0.029850692, -0.019150086, -0.022015542, -0.017329432, 0.01713435, -0.051847745, 0.04411004, 0.0043246513, -0.020672046, -0.05744984, 0.01616956, 0.003691678, -0.00086021295, -0.036128446, 0.010201146, -0.017065775, -0.007568712, 0.013267315, 0.010555285, 0.017778654, 0.01731557, 0.043128397, 0.053232398, -0.01074936, -0.02444354, 0.013700622, 0.026423648, -0.015820647, 0.028598722, 0.024576135, 0.013912596, -0.0008987383, 0.05605868, 0.026335739, 0.02005624, -0.06253853, 0.047632698, 0.041846883, 0.043078583, 0.011441847, -0.055134065, -0.008666394, -0.02314181, 0.011002701, -2.7868377e-06, -0.0055337064, 0.04209667, 0.027668161, 0.0009456976, 0.01698213, -0.020949444, 0.010950561, -0.002891666, 0.028498197, 0.017447267, -0.0066549424, 0.012107768, -0.01440909, 0.002223006, -0.04830412, 0.00021201241, -0.022676073, 0.00389171, -0.0189218, 0.025131913, -0.013154152, 0.040034153, 0.016872715, 0.044760298, -0.008609007, -0.012598484, 0.051026743, -0.025132865, 0.005154939, 0.051414255, -0.029149367, 0.0253